<div xmlns:java="http://xml.apache.org/xslt/java" id="centre_col"><!-- begin original content --><h1>ESSUM35830 - Requirements relating
to share options - exercise rights: Takeovers</h1>
<br>
<p>Most successful takeovers bids will trigger exercise by virtue
of paragraph 37 (2) and (6) successively. If the acquirer does not
already control the target:</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">its offer to acquire all the shares in the
target (or all the shares of a specific class conferring control)
and acceptance by enough shareholders to confer control on the
acquirer, will trigger the right of exercise under 37 (2).</li>
<li class="filledcircle">its receipt of acceptances in respect of
90% of the shares it did not hold when it made the offer, makes the
acquirer bound and entitled under Section 979 &ndash; 982 (squeeze
out provisions) of the Companies Act 2006 to acquire the shares of
the dissenting minority, and triggers a right of exercise under 37
(6).</li>
</ul>
<p>Exercise under (2), but not (6), will be triggered if control is
obtained as a result of a general offer but 90% acceptances are not

received.

<br>
<br> Exercise under (6), but not (2), will be triggered if the

acquirer already has control of the target when its offer is made

but receives 90% acceptances in respect of the shares it did not

hold when it made the offer.

<br>
<br> The period when the acquiring company is bound or entitled

under Sections 979 &ndash; 982 Companies Act 2006 may, in practice,

be much shorter than the six month period during which paragraph 37

(2) and the scheme rules may give the option-holder the right to

exercise.

<br>
<br> In practice it is not possible for a SAYE share option to be

part exercised and part rolled-over in these circumstances because

of the terms of the savings contracts (see 

<a href="ESSUM34170.htm">ESSUM34170</a>).

<br>
<br> If, as a result of a takeover, the scheme shares no longer

satisfy the requirements of paragraphs 18 &ndash; 22 Schedule 3

(for example if the scheme company becomes under the control of a

company not listed on a recognised stock exchange) options will

not, in practice, be capable of being exercised in accordance with

the scheme rules, notwithstanding that paragraph 37 (2) may have

triggered early exercise rights.</p>
<br>
